The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will come to an end, and the usual explanation is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club released the seminal work "The Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its fundamental ideas have been with us ever since.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 book "Limits to Growth" warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, what we saw afterward was a financial panic, but no real shortages or production collapse.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
But the core idea of "The Limits to Growth" remains valid: we continue a trend of focusing on misleading solutions to minor issues while neglecting major problems and wise resolutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public alarm about pollution and sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people concerned about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too much.
Even if our genius grants us some time, in the end, we will still destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to achieve social stability at a significantly poorer level by halting economic growth itself, reducing consumption, recycling resources, and forcing people to have fewer children.
This view still resonates today, even though it is profoundly mistaken.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that by 2013, the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of the level from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, leading to a 98% decline in mercury consumption and a 90% drop in its price by the year 2000.
More broadly speaking, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted by 1990 and 1992, respectively; however, reserves of both are now higher than the 1970 levels, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and halved the price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14-fold this century, with developing countries seeing a 24-fold increase.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has been slowing down since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are currently in use, in addition to 2.7 billion hectares of reserve land).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution hasn't stopped us either.
The Roman Club imagines a pastoral past where we had no airborne particulate pollution, and we were all happy farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys will make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the world's population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people — one in every 500 — died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Today, this ratio has dropped to one death in every 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that from malaria, the mortality rate from pollution is decreasing rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas fostered by "The Limits to Growth" continue to influence the thinking of both the public and the elite.
Take recycling as an example; it is often just a feel-good gesture that costs the environment a lot with little real benefit.
For example, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, while protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, concerns over overpopulation have led to self-defeating policies, such as China's family planning policy and India's forced sterilization programs.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to be responsible for killing half of the human population, effective pesticide regulation has limited annual deaths in the United States to just 20 cases. At the same time, the use of pesticides has created a cheaper and more abundant food supply.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — a movement driven by fear of pesticides — would impose an additional annual cost of $100 billion on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency will decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland will need to be cultivated—equivalent to half the area of modern-day California.
Price increases will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health effects, including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths each year.
Being obsessed with dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on real global threats.
Poverty is one of the greatest killers, and easily treatable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year — equivalent to a quarter of all deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
After people escape poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the global population living in poverty by nearly one billion.
This has led to widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more growth, not less.
The expansion of trade is estimated to generate over $10 trillion in annual benefits by the end of this century, far surpassing the timid "safe" policies driven by fear-mongering.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
